<p class="para"><i>The restless soul will soon invite crimson blood.
    <br>Angels feast upon the blood, guiding the plates that ignite.
    <br>Beneath a clouded sky, warlords clear their throats in silence.
    <br>With the goddess's tears, the four shrines are severed—
    <br>and the mother angel descends.</i></p>
<p class="para"><i>From the Tower of Crimson Lightning,
    <br>the dragon falls—
    <br>toward a point no one has ever seen.</i></p>
<img src="https://i.imgur.com/2BCjDAc.png">
<p class="title">Chapter 1</p>
<p class="para"><i>The restless soul will soon invite crimson blood.</i></p>
<img src="https://i.imgur.com/gqZH1lL.png">
<p class="1"></p>
<p class="para">With wings aglow, a bird soared through the vast sky.</p>
<p class="para">Though a thin veil of cloud stretched across it, the sky was boundless—and beautiful. So beautiful, in fact, that it was hard to believe the scene unfolding below belonged to the same world. The shouting, the blood spray—none of it reached this high. Not even the rising clouds of dust could touch this place.</p>
<p class="para">Before long, the bird began to circle lazily, as if mocking the humans below, then disappeared into the distance.</p>
<p class="para">"Infantry sighted ahead!"</p>
<p class="para">Down on the ground, no one noticed the bird in flight.
    <br>The only ones looking to the sky were the dead.
</p>
<p class="para">"Lord Caim, please be careful!"</p>
<p class="para">The voice that rang out belonged to a soldier long past the age for the battlefield. The one who answered him, in contrast, was a young man—still in the prime of youth.</p>
<p class="para">"Don’t falter—charge!"</p>
<p class="para">Yet despite his youth, his movements bore the mark of a seasoned warrior.
    <br>There was no hesitation in the path his blade carved.
    <br>He cut down foes without mercy, crushed them without pause.
    <br>Kicking aside fallen corpses, he pressed forward, sweeping through the enemies around him.
</p>
<p class="para">But no matter how many he cut down—no matter how many he left in his wake—the soldiers kept coming, spilling forth from nowhere, as if summoned by the battlefield itself.</p>
<p class="para">“Enemy reinforcements at the rear!”</p>
<p class="para">There was no time to listen. He focused solely on cutting down the enemy.</p>
<p class="para">“What strength… These things—these aren’t human!”</p>
<p class="para">Those red eyes were proof enough.
    <br>Whether they were born with such features or driven to this state by some sinister elixir, no one could say for sure.
</p>
<p class="para">A cry rose—half scream, half realization.
    <br>Yes, that’s right. They aren’t human.
    <br>They’re <i>ticks</i>. Imperial ticks.
</p>
<p class="para">And so, there was no place for guilt. No pang of conscience.
    <br>Even when he brought his blade down upon the skull of a trembling, retreating soldier, his hand didn’t waver.
</p>
<p class="para">Why is it that the blood and flesh of one’s enemies can feel so… gratifying?
    <br>The stench of blood that should be repulsive—the sensation of flesh splitting, of bone shattering—was nothing short of delightful.
    <br>For a moment, he almost forgot he was meant to be leading a battalion.
</p>
<p class="para">And yet, what was this endlessness?
    <br>He began to wonder if the very corpses he struck down weren’t simply rising to their feet again.
</p>
<p class="para">“The enemy’s breached the castle! At this rate, Lady Furiae—!”</p>
<p class="para">Then, from behind, something hit him with enormous force.
    <br>A jolt of numbness shot from his shoulder down his back.
    <br>Before he even realized he’d been cut, his sword was already in motion—
    <br>and with every last ounce of strength, he crushed the enemy soldier behind him.
</p>


<p class="para">Suddenly, the ground beneath his feet gave way.
    <br>He scrambled to steady himself—falling now would mean instant death.
</p>
<p class="para">His sword arm had gone strangely rigid.
    <br>There wasn’t much pain, but each breath came harder than the last.
    <br>He drew air through clenched teeth, bracing both feet.
    <br>He couldn’t allow himself to fall. Not here.
</p>
<p class="para">He lifted his head, just as he moved to raise his sword again—
    <br>and saw it.
    <br>The banner over the castle gate was engulfed in flames.
    <br>The enemy had set it alight.
</p>
<p class="para">The banner blazing.
    <br>Flaming arrows raining down.
    <br>Chaos.
    <br>Blood.
    <br>And then—
    <br>…his parents’ death.
</p>
<p class="para">“Furiae…”</p>
<p class="para">In that moment, the memory surged back to life—and strength flooded his limbs.
    <br>Caim took off, running without thinking.
</p>
<p class="para">Toward the goddess Furiae—
    <br>his sister.
    <br>The only family he had left in this world.
</p>
<p class="title">2</p>
<p class="para">When do people realize that they were no longer children, that the childhood that would seem like it would last forever was long gone?</p>
<p class="para">Caim thinks that he realized this too late. Being blessed with too much can spoil a person and sometimes hinder their growth. He was born into a royal family, and although the country was small, he grew up without want. His father, King Gaap, was a master of martial arts but also gentle, two qualities that were often contradictory in any other king, and was highly praised as a wise ruler.</p>
<p class="para">The kingdom was prosperous, and its relations with neighboring nations were peaceful.</p>
<p class="para">Had he known the loneliness so often tied to royal succession, things might have turned out differently.
    <br>But Caim had a friend—his name was Inuart.
</p>
<p class="para">Among all his vassals, King Gaap trusted none more than Inuart’s father, Ipris.
    <br>He named Ipris Prime Minister, and treated Inuart as if he were his own son.
</p>
<p class="para">Gaap himself had been raised by the previous king, a strict man who valued rank and lineage above all else.
    <br>As a result, Gaap grew to adulthood without knowing what true friendship was. Even after ascending the throne at a young age, it took time before he found anyone he could truly call a confidant.
</p>
<p class="para">Perhaps that was why he so deeply wished for his son, Caim, to have someone he could trust from an early age.
    <br>Even a king doesn’t want his child to suffer as he once did.
</p>
<p class="para">Whether by fate or the king’s intention, that wish came true—Caim and Inuart became the closest of friends.
    <br>They played together endlessly in the palace gardens, and now and then got into mischief, earning scoldings from the head maidservant. In time, Furiae was born, and their duo became a trio.
</p>
<p class="para">Once Furiae was old enough to run on her own, the three of them came up with a plan: they would sneak out of the palace.
    <br>They’d hide in the back of a merchant’s wagon—one of the regular traders who came and went.
</p>
<p class="para">As long as they kept quiet in the bed of the cart, they could slip past the guards at the rear gate and evade the patrols near the palace grounds.
    <br>Then, when the wagon slowed, they would leap off and dash away.
</p>
<p class="para">It worked.</p>
<p class="para">On the way back, they would return through the main gate, heads held high, asking the guards to open it as if they’d simply exited through another door.</p>
<p class="para">However, as their antics repeated, even the gatekeepers began to grow suspicious. Eventually, one of them reported the matter to the head maid, and the trio’s “unauthorized excursions” came to light. From that day on, all merchant wagons entering the palace had their cargo thoroughly inspected.</p>
<p class="para">On another occasion, the three came up with a new idea—digging a tunnel beneath the castle walls to sneak out. But no sooner had they started than a gardener caught them, and they were soundly scolded once again.</p>
<p class="para">Every time Inuart’s “misdeeds” came to light, his father, Ipris, would go pale and beg forgiveness. But King Gaap would simply laugh with an air of generosity.</p>
<p class="para">“It’s nothing to worry about. If they lack the cunning to slip past a guard’s notice, I’d be more concerned for their future.
    <br>More importantly, childhood friends are treasures for life. There’s no need to take it so seriously.”
</p>
<p class="para">After saying this, it was his habit to turn to the queen at his side for agreement.</p>
<p class="para">Caim’s mother had come from a neighboring kingdom to marry King Gaap. Accompanying her at that time had been the woman who now served as the head maid. It was said that Caim’s mother and the head maid had grown up together like sisters, their bond as close as family.</p>
<p class="para">In time, King Gaap began personally teaching Caim and Inuart the art of the sword. Thus, the two boys were not only playmates but rivals as well.</p>
<p class="para">King Gaap was one of the most accomplished swordsmen in the history of the royal line, and his son Caim, bearing that blood, showed remarkable talent—so much so that it astonished those around him. Inuart, too, improved quickly and became a skilled swordsman in his own right, but no matter how hard he tried, he could never best Caim. When Caim suggested it was simply the difference in their age, Inuart, frustrated by the truth of it, would throw himself even more fervently into their matches.</p>
<p class="para">Even so, nothing ever came between them. Their friendship remained strong.</p>
<p class="para">Still, if they kept sparring forever, Furiae—waiting for them to finish—would grow restless. Having been part of their lives since she could remember, Furiae didn’t take kindly to being left out while the boys trained.</p>
<p class="para">“This is boring! All you two ever do is practice with swords.”</p>
<p class="para">With her arms crossed and her cheeks puffed in a pout, it usually fell to Inuart to calm her down.</p>
<p class="para">That was because Inuart had a gift Caim did not—he could sing.
    <br>No matter how long she had waited, the moment Inuart strummed his harp and began to sing,
    <br>Furiae’s mood would soften immediately.
</p>
<p class="para">“Sing more.”</p>
<p class="para">Whatever sulking she’d been doing was forgotten in an instant as she asked for the next song.
    <br>And then another. And another after that.
    <br>Such was the power of Inuart’s voice—it captivated the heart and refused to let go.
</p>
<p class="para">It seemed he had inherited his musical talent from his mother’s side.
    <br>His maternal grandfather had been a celebrated harpist, and his late aunt—who died young—
    <br>had once been known as a songstress of the royal court.
</p>
<p class="para">Though it wasn’t only his music that charmed her, of course…
    <br>In time, Inuart and Furiae began to share the tender feelings of childhood love.
</p>
<p class="para">King Gaap welcomed the budding relationship between his daughter and the only son of his loyal vassal, Ipris. Though the wedding itself was still far off, they were not too young to be betrothed.</p>
<p class="para"><i>Inuart is a good match.</i></p>
<p class="para">That was Caim’s honest thought when he first learned of their engagement. The two knew each other well, and there was no reason to believe Inuart would ever bring unhappiness to Furiae.
    <br>Their parents approved, and everyone in the palace offered blessings and kind words.
    <br>The quiet ache Caim felt in the corner of his heart, he told himself, must have been nothing more than a pang of loneliness—the sorrow of three becoming two and one.
    <br>Perhaps, at last, he could understand what Furiae had felt as she waited alone during those long hours of sword training.
</p>
<p class="para">But never did he imagine that this engagement would cast a shadow over the bond the three of them had shared—one that had once seemed unbreakable.</p>
<p class="para">The change came gradually—something began to twist, to fray. And looking back on it now, it was all painfully simple.</p>
<p class="para">Inuart wanted to become two and one. Caim accepted that.</p>
<p class="para">But Furiae did not.</p>
<p class="para">That was all it was.</p>
<p class="para">Caim believed it perfectly natural that Inuart would want to have Furiae to himself. But Furiae was still a child.
    <br>She didn’t want things to change. She still wanted to be spoiled by both her brother and her childhood friend, just as she always had.
</p>
<p class="para">And when he thought about her age, Caim couldn’t help but feel… maybe that wasn’t so unreasonable after all.</p>
<p class="para">Unfortunately, Inuart lacked the maturity to accept Furiae’s childishness. He wasn’t a child, but he wasn’t quite an adult either.
    <br>That awkward age left him without the patience to bear with her.
    <br>Unable to have Furiae all to himself, Inuart turned his frustration on Caim.
    <br>And Caim, for his part, couldn't bring himself to calmly reason with his sister or forgive his friend’s misplaced accusations.
    <br>He wasn’t that much of an adult either.
</p>
<p class="para"><i>We have to grow up.</i>
<br><i>The days of carefree laughter and playful scuffles are over.</i></p>
<p class="para">By the time Caim realized that, the rift between him and Inuart had already grown too wide to mend.</p>
<p class="para">Their conversations turned stiff and unnatural. When they sparred, it always became hostile.
    <br>No matter what he did, it only seemed to make things worse.
    <br>…Where had it gone wrong? What mistake had he made?
</p>
<p class="para">Clashing blades with Inuart, Caim felt a rising storm of frustration and despair.
    <br>This was no longer practice. It was a real fight.
</p>
<p class="para">There was hatred in Inuart’s eyes—and Caim was certain his own eyes mirrored it.</p>
<p class="para"><i>Why?</i>
<br>Why have we come to hate each other so much?</p>
<p class="para">At this rate, he might actually kill Inuart.</p>
<p class="para">Caim knew his own skill with the sword was superior.
    <br>If he kept going like this…
    <br>A chilling sense of dread swept through him. It dulled his blade for the briefest moment. Created an opening.
</p>
<p class="para">Then he heard a sound—not the sharp ring of clashing steel, but something else entirely.</p>
<p class="para">Heat seared into his right shoulder.
    <br>The pain hit a moment later.
    <br>He dropped to his knees without meaning to.
</p>
<p class="para">“Caim…”</p>
<p class="para">The bloodstained sword slipped from Inuart’s hand.
    <br>The soldiers standing by rushed forward in a panic.
</p>
<p class="para">“I’m fine… don’t worry,”
    <br>Caim managed to say—just barely.
</p>
<p class="para">It wasn’t a serious wound.
    <br>The royal physician judged that it wouldn’t take long to heal, and everyone breathed a sigh of relief.
    <br>Given the circumstances, Caim insisted it was an accident—that he’d been distracted during sparring with live blades—and King Gaap accepted his explanation without question. He never once considered punishing Inuart.
</p>
<p class="para">But there were two people who couldn’t forgive him.</p>
<p class="para">One was Ipris.
    <br>Even if it had been an accident, he argued, Inuart still had to take responsibility.
    <br>He ordered his son to remain confined under house arrest for the time being.
    <br>As a loyal subject, Ipris could not overlook what had happened.
</p>
<p class="para">The other was Furiae.</p>
<p class="para">Overwhelmed with worry for her brother, she had lashed out at Inuart with bitter accusations.
    <br>Caim hadn’t been there to see it, but the moment he saw his sister’s face the next morning, he knew exactly what had happened.
</p>
<p class="para">“What did you say to Inuart?”</p>
<p class="para">“Nothing,” Furiae replied, not meeting Caim’s eyes.</p>
<p class="para">And that was all the confirmation he needed.</p>
<p class="para">“It wasn’t Inuart’s fault. It was an accident.”</p>
<p class="para">“But…”</p>
<p class="para">“Make up with him.”</p>
<p class="para">Furiae lowered her head.</p>
<p class="para">“You know you went too far, don’t you?”</p>
<p class="para">“That’s not true. Inuart was the one at fault. Because…”</p>
<p class="para">“Because?”</p>
<p class="para">“Because today is your birthday, Caim-nii-sama! It’s awful… for something like this to happen today…”</p>
<p class="para">Caim let out a wry laugh.
    <br>He couldn’t help but find his sister amusing—dragging up something completely unrelated just so she wouldn’t have to admit she’d gone too far.
</p>
<p class="para">“So it would’ve been fine if it weren’t my birthday?”</p>
<p class="para">He teased her gently, and Furiae fell silent.
    <br>But she quickly found something else to say, and opened her mouth again.
</p>
<p class="para">“But because of your injury, the celebration got canceled!”</p>
<p class="para">Caim’s eighteenth birthday had been declared a national holiday.
    <br>A grand feast was supposed to be held at the royal palace.
    <br>But out of concern for his son, King Gaap had abruptly called it off.
</p>
<p class="para">Instead, King Gaap had granted the vassals and soldiers a day of rest.</p>
<p class="para">“Then I guess we should be thanking Inuart,” Caim said. “I was never too fond of banquets anyway.”</p>
<p class="para">As he gently teased his sister, he realized the tightness in his chest had finally begun to ease.
    <br>It was strange—almost like something had been exorcised.
    <br>For the first time in what felt like ages, he thought they might be able to laugh together again, like they used to.
    <br>Inuart might not be ready to reconcile just yet, but Caim felt he could wait patiently.
</p>
<p class="para">Now that he thought about it, he hadn’t felt this calm in a long time.
    <br>Ever since the engagement between Inuart and Furiae, something inside him had always felt jagged, raw.
    <br>But now, it was gone—completely, without a trace.
    <br>Maybe he was finally ready to grow up.
    <br>And if that was the case, then it wasn’t such a bad birthday after all.
</p>
<p class="para">Sunlight streamed gently through the windows, and a peaceful stillness hung over the palace.
    <br>Caim silently offered his gratitude to his father, the king, for giving him such a restful day.
</p>
<p class="para">But only a few hours later, everything changed.</p>
<p class="para">While Caim and his family were enjoying a quiet moment together in the palace courtyard…
    <br>The Reaper cloaked in pitch-black descended from the sky.
</p>
<p class="para">The Black Dragon.</p>
<p class="para">Not just Caim and Furiae, but likely even their parents—this was probably the first time any of them had ever seen one with their own eyes.
    <br>Dragons were said to be divine messengers, rarely appearing before humans.
</p>
<p class="para">Which is why, when that black-winged creature came gliding down from the sky…
    <br>None of them were prepared.
</p>
<p class="para">After all, the idea that a divine messenger would attack unarmed humans was beyond imagining.</p>
<p class="para">It all happened in an instant.
    <br>A black whirlwind swept through them.
    <br>Time stood still.
</p>
<p class="para">In the next moment, Caim saw red flash across his wide-open eyes.
    <br>The dragon tore his mother apart with its claws, then lunged at his father with its razor-sharp fangs.
    <br>He heard himself screaming.
</p>
<p class="para">The dragon turned to look at him—its eyes blazed with a brilliant, hellish red.</p>
<p class="para">That was the last thing Caim remembered.</p>
<p class="para">When he came to, the Black Dragon had already vanished into the sky.</p>
<p class="para">Furiae stood beside him, pale and shaking. Pain seared through his right shoulder.
    <br>He couldn’t remember what he’d done, only that his wound was bleeding freely.
</p>
<p class="para">Drops of blood trickled down his fingers.
    <br>Forgetting even to press against the wound, Caim walked toward the bodies of his father and mother.
    <br>He knelt beside them. Held them.
</p>
<p class="para">They no longer breathed.
    <br>Their eyes were still open in shock.
    <br>He gently reached out to close their lids.
</p>
<p class="para">He couldn’t bring himself to rage or weep.
    <br>He simply stared at their corpses.
</p>
<p class="para">After King Gaap's death, the kingdom fell into ruin with shocking speed.</p>
<p class="para">Though the land was fertile, the country had always been small.
    <br>Its peaceful relations with neighboring states had been entirely thanks to the king’s personal diplomacy.
</p>
<p class="para">In every sense of the word, Gaap had been the linchpin of the realm.</p>
<p class="para">The prime minister, Ipris, took over the reins of government, but he could not take the king’s place.</p>
<p class="para">Perhaps things might have gone differently if Caim had ascended the throne as the new king once the mourning period ended.</p>
<p class="para">Loyal retainers still remained at court, and though Caim was young, the people pinned their hopes on the prince who carried King Gaap’s blood.</p>
<p class="para">But Caim did not take up that role.
    <br>He <i>couldn’t.</i>
</p>
<p class="para">If only the celebration had gone ahead as planned that day.
    <br>If only they hadn’t gone out into the courtyard.
</p>
<p class="para">It had been his own fault they’d ended up outside, without even a guard posted.
    <br>The Black Dragon may have killed his parents, but wasn’t he complicit in that tragedy?
</p>
<p class="para">With such thoughts in his heart, how could he possibly take up his father’s crown?</p>
<p class="para">And that wasn’t all.</p>
<p class="para">After King Gaap's death, the royal court became awash with wild rumors.
    <br>Some claimed the Black Dragon had been sent by a fanatical cult.
    <br>Others said it was divine punishment from the goddess of the seal, Asherah, who had harbored a forbidden love for Gaap.
    <br>Still others whispered that it was Prime Minister Ipris who summoned the monster through some sinister rite, as part of a treasonous plot.
</p>
<p class="para">No matter how hard Caim tried to shut them out, the rumors always reached his ears.
    <br>What stung the most were those claiming that Ipris had incited his son Inuart to wound Caim.
    <br>They said Ipris had orchestrated the cancellation of the banquet and kept the palace free of soldiers, all part of his scheme.
</p>
<p class="para">And there was more still.
    <br>Back when Gaap had been a prince, it was said he and Ipris had been bitter enemies.
    <br>Despite the prime minister’s outward show of loyalty, perhaps he had been biding his time all along, waiting for the chance to bring Gaap down.
</p>
<p class="para">There were even those who whispered, saying that Ipris had been waiting for his chance all along.</p>
<p class="para">Most of it was, in all likelihood, nothing more than groundless rumor.
    <br>But to those who do not know the truth, every rumor has a ring of plausibility to it.
    <br>And it is said that no matter how steeped in falsehood, a rumor always contains at least a sliver of truth.
    <br>Some even say that rumors are the desires of the people themselves.
</p>
<p class="para">That Ipris was a traitor was a claim hard to believe on its face.</p>
<p class="para">Yet it was true that he would have known the palace guard was thin that day—
    <br>and that Caim and his family were passing the afternoon in the courtyard.
    <br>That precisely timed assault…
    <br>If the rumors were true—
</p>
<p class="para">Unable to bear the growing weight of doubt day after day,
    <br>Caim went to Ipris and asked him directly:
    <br>Was it true that he had once been an enemy of his father?
</p>
<p class="para">Caim had expected him to deny it without hesitation.
    <br>But Ipris answered otherwise.
</p>
<p class="para">“It is true. But I knelt before the king and swore loyalty and obedience.
    <br>It is precisely because one is an enemy… that a bond can be born.”
</p>
<p class="para">Caim could not take those words at face value.
    <br>Rather, he resented Ipris for not denying it—even if it had only been a lie.
</p>
<p class="para">Caim resented Ipris.
    <br>And he came to loathe the retainers who brought him these troubling rumors.
    <br>He could no longer bring himself to trust anyone.
</p>
<p class="para">Caim avoided facing Inuart as much as he could.
    <br>If he opened his mouth, he would surely say something that could never be taken back.
    <br>More than anything, he feared that if he truly faced Inuart, he would come to hate him in earnest.
</p>
<p class="para">After all, it was Inuart who had wounded him to begin with.</p>
<p class="para">Just before the tragedy, Caim had thought the bitterness he felt toward Inuart had finally begun to fade.
    <br>He had started to believe that one day, they might again laugh together as they once had, and speak to one another as they used to.
    <br>He had resolved to wait patiently for that day to come.
    <br>But now—what had that even been?
    <br>Looking back, all that filled him was emptiness.</p>
<p class="para">It was then, as if to mock his hopes, that civil war broke out.
    <br>One faction sought to install Caim as the new king,
    <br>while another desired that Prime Minister Ipris continue his rule.
    <br>The conflict escalated into armed violence.
    <br>Yet Caim himself had no part in it—he hadn’t even been aware it was happening.
</p>
<p class="para">The rebellion grew with each passing day,
    <br>and eventually, even the royal palace was touched by the flames of war.
    <br>At last, Ipris called upon a neighboring king to send reinforcements.
    <br>The uprising was suppressed,
    <br>but with it, the nation itself began to crumble in earnest.
</p>
<p class="para">That was when Caim made up his mind to leave the palace.</p>
<p class="para">His very existence—regardless of his own will—was being used as justification for war.
    <br>That was something he could never accept.
    <br>If he remained in the palace, the same thing would surely happen again…
</p>
<p class="para">And so, one morning, Caim departed without a word.
    <br>He told no one—not even Inuart, not even the retainers.
    <br>It had been nearly a full year since the day his parents were killed.
</p>
<p class="para">He had intended to leave alone.
    <br>He had no destination in mind, no path laid before him.
    <br>He needed no companion.
</p>
<p class="para">The only one he confided in was Furiae—
