</p>
<p class="para">That’s why, Furiae said, with a small smile,</p>
<p class="para">“Let’s just live as normal people. I never want to go through something like that again…”</p>
<p class="para">Wandering in a foreign land, lineage means nothing.
    <br>There’s no need to declare you’re living as a commoner—
    <br>and yet, by saying it out loud, Furiae was perhaps trying to ease the fear of leaving behind a life of comfort.
</p>
<p class="para">“Hey… it’s a good idea, don’t you think?”</p>
<p class="para">When their parents had been attacked, he hadn’t been able to do a thing. He couldn’t protect the country, couldn’t protect the people. So at the very least—from this day forward—he would protect his sister, Furiae. The only family he had left.</p>
<p class="para">“Brother (Caim-nii-sama). No…Caim (Nii-san).”</p>
<p class="para">Furiae gave a bashful smile. And in that moment, Caim prayed from the bottom of his heart that her smile would never fade again.</p>
<p class="para">They were nearing the border when they saw it:
    <br>a black flag fluttering over the worship site.
    <br>Beneath the overcast sky, the sight gave off a quiet, foreboding weight.
    <br>It was likely that every shrine and temple, in every land, now flew the same black banner.
</p>
<p class="para">“The Goddess, Asherah, is dead.”</p>
<p class="para">Furiae’s voice was heavy.
    <br>Perhaps she was recalling the rumor that the goddess Asherah had once loved King Gaap.
</p>
<p class="para">“The Goddess of the Seal… Hmph. Maybe the world never really needed something like that to begin with.”</p>
<p class="para">In this world, what binds the Great Time—the source of order—to its rightful place
are the three seals held in the temples of forest, desert, and sea.
<br>And the goddess’s life itself.</p>
<p class="para">Once all the seals within the temples were undone, and the goddess’s life was lost, the “Great Time” would be unmoored from its rightful place, plunging the world into chaos. And when all living things stood on the brink of annihilation, it was said that the hand of god would give birth to an egg of rebirth (seeds of resurrection), bringing new order to the world once more.</p>
<p class="para">If the world was just going to be reborn by divine will anyway, then what was the point of the seals to begin with? That was how Caim saw it.</p>
<p class="para">
The goddess of the seal—said to exist only once in any given era—had originally been just a normal person. A woman living an ordinary life, suddenly declared a goddess, and imprisoned deep within a temple. From that moment on, she was cut off entirely from the world. She could never again see her family, her lover, or anyone she’d once known.
<br>For the woman forced into that role—and for those around her—what greater tragedy could there be?
<br>If the seals had never existed in the first place… then neither would such tragedies.</p>
<p class="para">“You mustn’t say things like that.”</p>
<p class="para">Furiae looked around, flustered. She probably didn’t want him speaking so irreverently in front of the people paying their respects at the shrine.</p>
<p class="para">“The gods want us humans to protect the world with our own hands. That’s what Mother—no, what Mom always used to say.”</p>
<p class="para">“Count me out. What’s the point, if it’s all just going to be reborn anyway?”</p>
<p class="para">“Brother!”</p>
<p class="para">“Now if <i>you</i> ever got chosen as the next goddess or whatever, I’d grab you and run before they could lay a finger on you. I mean—what’s the point in suffering through all that, when the egg of rebirth’s just gonna hatch (the seeds of resurrection will be sown) if we wait it out anyway?”</p>
<p class="para">Furiae shot him a glare. Caim shrugged exaggeratedly in response.</p>
<p class="para">There’d never been a story of a goddess candidate escaping her fate.
    <br>Were they really all so dull-witted that the thought never even crossed their minds?
    <br>Or perhaps—any such attempts had simply been buried in secrecy.
</p>
<p class="para">“Well, either way, it’s got nothing to do with us.”</p>
<p class="para">The sky began to darken all of a sudden. Rain was probably coming. Wanting to get inside before it hit, the two hurried toward the inn.</p>
<p class="para">The disturbance came sometime after midnight.
    <br>He thought he heard Furiae scream.
</p>
<p class="para">Caim jolted upright in the dark.
    <br>He reached blindly for the candlestick—
    <br>No. He didn’t need a light.
    <br>There was already a pale glow spilling from the corner of the room.
