<p class="para">“You’re wrong. She’s just sick. Now go—leave us!”</p>
<p class="para">Caim rushed back into the room and bolted the door from the inside. His hands were shaking—so hard, he could see it clearly.</p>
<p class="para">“Furiae…”</p>
<p class="para">There was no response. Perhaps even groaning had become too painful—Furiae lay still, her eyes closed, limp and motionless. No… no, this can’t be happening… Unable to bear it, Caim buried his face in his hands. Every single word he had spoken earlier that day now pierced through him like sharpened arrows.</p>
<p class="para">A knock sounded from behind. “Please open the door,” came the priest’s voice.</p>
<p class="para">“Go away!”</p>
<p class="para">He shouted toward the door. He wouldn’t give her up. The sealed goddess wasn’t merely forbidden from contact with the world of man—he had heard that the pain brought by the sealing power would torment her constantly… and that she wouldn’t live long.</p>
<p class="para">Even if the world were to collapse, he could never let his sister shoulder such a cruel fate.</p>
<p class="para">Yes… he just had to do what he’d said earlier. He’d run. Take Furiae and flee.</p>
<p class="para">“If we do nothing, her life is in danger.”</p>
<p class="para">Caim lifted his head. What was that supposed to mean?</p>
<p class="para">“The rite of transference isn’t complete. Unless the High Priest intervenes directly, the seal cannot be finalized. An incomplete seal… will consume the goddess’s life.”</p>
<p class="para">His hand, trembling, reached out and touched Furiae’s cheek. Cold. Just like when he had lifted his mother’s lifeless body from the palace courtyard… it was the very same chill.</p>
<p class="para">“Please, I beg you—make haste. The High Priest’s party is already on their way to this town.”</p>
<p class="para">Now he understood why no goddess candidate had ever escaped.</p>
<p class="para">It wasn’t that they wouldn’t.
    <br>It was that they couldn’t—in this condition.
</p>
<p class="para">But even if they tried to run—what difference would it make? The priests would come for them without delay. Just like now. They’d already arrived, far too quickly to be coincidence.</p>
<p class="para">“Even if you can’t see her again… she’ll still be alive. That much won’t change.”</p>
<p class="para">The priest's voice, which had remained calm and detached until now, wavered slightly with the faintest trace of compassion. No doubt he'd spoken these words many times before, watched others accept this same cruel parting with quiet resignation.
    <br>Even if they were never to reunite—if she could just live on.
    <br>Even if that life meant enduring unrelenting pain and isolation.
</p>
<p class="para">He had lost both parents in a single day. Furiae was all he had left. And now, even she was being taken from him.</p>
<p class="para">…But still—if she could just stay alive..</p>
<p class="para">“Furiae… forgive me.”</p>
<p class="para">He had failed to protect her. Worse—he was about to cast her into the very heart of despair with his own two hands. All because he couldn’t bear to lose another family member in front of his eyes.</p>
<p class="para">At some point, he realized he’d been clutching her hand. Gently, he let go. Slowly, he stood. Walked over to the door.
    <br>And then—Caim undid the latch.
</p>
<p class="para">A month passed.</p>
<p class="para">In a far-off country, Caim heard whispers—rumors that a queen had been slaughtered by a Black Dragon. That behind the scenes, a strange, sinister faction was moving—one that commanded “soldiers with crimson eyes.”
    <br>They were called the Empire (Imperial Army). And their power was growing stronger with every passing day.
</p>
<p class="para">And so, Caim became a mercenary.
    <br>Now that he knew who had been pulling the strings, there was no way he could remain silent.
</p>
<p class="para">He would kill as many Imperial soldiers as he could.
    <br>That was the only way to ease the anger and hatred smoldering inside him—the rage of losing his parents, his kingdom, and finally, his sister, without being able to do a thing to stop it.
    <br>He had no choice but to let the word “revenge” stand in for everything.
</p>
<p class="para">He tore across the battlefield, relentlessly, killing Imperial soldiers without end.
    <br>No word ever reached him of his homeland. No sign of Inuart.
    <br>Only time moved forward.
    <br>And so, six years had passed.
</p>
<p class="title">3</p>
<p class="para">The goddess lives out her brief life deep within the temple.
    <br>Hidden away, untouched by the world of mortals, she spends her days in silence.
    <br>The previous goddess, Asherah, had lived and died like so.
</p>
<p class="para">But after Furiae became the new goddess, an unexpected crisis arose—the Empire began its invasion.
    <br>From somewhere, a rumor spread: the Empire was after the sealed goddess.
    <br>Indeed, their advancing path was headed straight for the temple.
    <br>A sanctuary meant for prayer and worship had no means to defend itself; if attacked, it would surely fall.
</p>
<p class="para">And so, the high priest took action to relocate the goddess.
    <br>She was hidden away within a fortified citadel, protected by natural cliffs and deep moats.
    <br>The Union forces poured as much of their military might into the castle as possible, assigning troops to guard her.
    <br>Even the rapidly growing Empire would think twice before making a move against such a stronghold…
</p>
<p class="para">And yet, the Empire laid siege to the castle with a force that defied all reason. Upon hearing the news, Caim had rushed to join the reinforcements. But by the time they arrived, the defenses had already fallen one by one—and before his very eyes, the castle gates were breached.</p>
<p class="para">He’d only been able to scatter the enemy in a blind frenzy for a fleeting moment. By the time he managed to roll through the gate, it was painfully clear—he’d taken a grave wound.</p>
<p class="para">It felt like swinging a sword while freezing in some arctic wasteland. With each strike, his arms grew heavier; his legs dragged like they’d been shackled in lead. And on top of that, the crushing shortness of breath. Still, Caim ran. Still, he swung his blade.</p>
<p class="para">Furiae was most likely in the topmost tower. In a siege, that would be the only place to flee. But would he have the strength to make it there?</p>
<p class="para">Now and then, the sounds around him would recede, distant and muffled. Maybe sweat had gotten in his eyes—his vision was blurred. And yet, he still managed to cut down his enemies, and found himself equal parts amazed and exasperated. Maybe those five long years as a mercenary hadn’t been for nothing.</p>
<p class="para">Suddenly, the corridor ended, and light spilled into his vision. He had emerged into the courtyard. This was bad. Unlike the narrow passageways, the open courtyard could easily be surrounded. But did he even have the strength left to take a longer path around?</p>
<p class="para">The keep was still far off. Time was running out.</p>
<p class="para">No, he thought, better to go around. It would be smarter. He turned on his heel, ready to trust in what strength he had left—</p>
<p class="para">And stopped.</p>
<p class="para">“…A dragon.”</p>
<p class="para">He thought at first it was a hallucination brought on by blood loss. Or maybe some other wild beast held captive. But no—mistaking a dragon was impossible, even for him. Not with <i>those</i> scales. <i>Those</i> claws. Its back was riddled with arrows, its body bound in countless chains, but there was no mistaking it.</p>
<p class="para">The Red Dragon.</p>
<p class="para">Its scales shimmered like distilled night, its eyes blazing crimson. A vision surfaced in Caim’s mind—those jaws clamped around his father’s throat, those claws rending open his mother’s chest…</p>
<p class="para">The dragon. This was the one.</p>
<p class="para">The one that took their parents from him and Furiae. The one that took peace, and country, and everything else from the people.</p>
<p class="para">Caim stepped into the courtyard. It didn’t matter if the enemy saw him. It didn’t matter if he was surrounded. He pressed forward on unsteady legs. Toward the source of it all. The one that stole everything. The one that shattered everything—</p>
<p class="para">It would pay. Here and now. He would make it pay. With pain. With death.</p>
<p class="para">"Kill me if you so desire..."</p>
<p class="para">The voice snapped him back to himself.</p>
<p class="para">Sword raised mid-swing, Caim lowered his gaze.</p>
<p class="para">"But…"</p>
<p class="para">Perhaps even speaking had become a torment—
    <br>For the dragon’s voice was ragged, cracked to the point of breaking. With each breath, thick red-black drops spilled onto the ground.
</p>
<p class="para">“You may take my life, but you will never taint my soul, wretched human.”</p>
<p class="para">And yet, it still tried to lift its head with what strength remained—
    <br>Perhaps it could not bear the thought of being looked down upon by something as lowly as a human.
</p>
<p class="para">Because his parents had been killed by one, Caim had always seen dragons as nothing more than beasts. But that wasn’t the truth.
    <br>They were creatures of vast longevity and immense intelligence—the mightiest beings in existence.
</p>
<p class="para">They were dragons—noble creatures once called <i>messengers of the gods</i>.</p>
<p class="para">There was no doubt: this Red Dragon had been captured by the Empire.
    <br>The Union, protectors of the Goddess of the Seal, would never have dared lay chains on a divine beast.
    <br>The Empire had taken it—brought it here to the battlefield, hoping to bend it to their will.
    <br>Or perhaps, judging by the blood-stained sigils scrawled into the earth, they meant to use it in some kind of ritual.
</p>
<p class="para">“Tell me, do you still want to live, dragon?”</p>
<p class="para">Caim asked, blade still raised.</p>
<p class="para">This dragon had clearly refused to bow to the Empire. This—this was the result.
    <br>Even if he didn’t strike it down now, it would die soon enough.
    <br>And he… he was no different.
    <br>In this state, he couldn’t hope to reach the castle—let alone protect Furiae.
</p>
<p class="para">“A pact! There’s no other way.”</p>
<p class="para">For both of them, this was the only path to survival.</p>
<p class="para">The dragon’s massive neck swayed slightly, as if in dark amusement.</p>
<p class="para">A <i>pact</i>—the act of exchanging hearts with something not human, and gaining a new power together.</p>
<p class="para">That’s what people said.
    <br>Whether such a thing was truly possible—whether one could even exchange hearts in the first place—Caim had no idea.
</p>
<p class="para">“What makes you think you are worthy of a pact with me?”</p>
<p class="para">The dragon let out a small sigh, what seemed to be a snort.</p>
<p class="para">“I’m not.”</p>
<p class="para">Worthiness? Who cares about that?</p>
<p class="para">He leveled his blade at the dragon’s snout.
    <br>He knew full well this wasn’t a creature that could be threatened with force.
</p>
<p class="para">“I…”</p>
<p class="para">To make a pact—to bind his life to the very dragon that had killed his parents…</p>
<p class="para">If that was <i>unthinkable</i>, then no one was more unworthy than he was.</p>
<p class="para">But even so—</p>
<p class="para">“Worthy or not, I wish to live. Despise me if you will, but I shall not die…!”</p>
<p class="para">He didn’t want to die. Not yet.
    <br>Not until he had his revenge.
</p>
<p class="para">Not until he’d wiped out the Empire’s soldiers with his own hands.
    <br>Until then—
</p>
<p class="para">He couldn’t die.</p>
<p class="para">“Your answer!”</p>
<p class="para">I will live.
    <br>No matter what it takes—I’ll survive.
</p>
<p class="para">“A pact? Or death?”</p>
<p class="para">The clink of armor sounded behind him.
    <br>The dragon shut its eyes.
