<p class="para">“Very well… a pact.”</p>
<p class="para">Caim’s right hand slipped from his sword—not by choice.
    <br>It moved on its own, as if pulled by some unseen force.
</p>
<p class="para">His fingertips were drawn toward his left breast.</p>
<p class="para">So this is how it’s done, he thought.
    <br>It didn’t matter that he didn’t know the process. It would happen anyway.
</p>
<p class="para">His bones and flesh screamed in unison.
    <br>As the pain reached its peak—agony like his body was being ripped apart—he felt something grasped in his right hand.
</p>
<p class="para">The light was too bright to keep his eyes open.
    <br>It pierced straight into his skull, like arrows into his eyeballs.
    <br>Whatever his right hand now held—whatever pulsed and throbbed with a living rhythm—was radiating that searing light.
</p>
<p class="para">His legs moved on their own.
    <br>Before he knew it, there was a similar orb of light at the end of his outstretched right hand.
    <br>His eyes burned. Unable to bear it, he shut them tight.
    <br>Even then, the light was blinding.
</p>
<p class="para">When the inside of his eyelids turned as white as snow, the light suddenly vanished.
    <br>His empty right hand hung in midair.
    <br>Caim instinctively looked between his hands.
    <br>He clenched his fist, then opened it.
    <br>The sensation of being controlled, as though by some outside force, was completely gone.
    <br>The searing pain that had threatened to devour him had disappeared without a trace.
    <br>There was no more difficulty breathing.
    <br>In an instant, his wounds had healed.
</p>
<p class="para">By his side, countless arrows and chains wrapped in coils snapped apart with a loud sound.
    <br>Wings, unscathed and unmarred, spread wide.
    <br>A roar shook the very air.
    <br>The dragon turned to him, as if to say, "Get on."
    <br>As Caim leapt onto her back, her wings cut through the air, and they took off.
</p>
<p class="para">The first flight was surprisingly brief.
    <br>The sound of the wind roared in his ears. They soared in a graceful arc, but before long, they began descending.
    <br>With a single burst of flame, the dragon incinerated the Imperial soldiers near the keep, then landed gently.
</p>
<p class="para">The distance from the courtyard to the innermost keep was covered in an instant.
    <br>A long, seemingly impossible distance that just moments ago had seemed so uncertain.
    <br>Caim couldn’t help but chuckle inwardly. Of course, a dragon would look down upon humans.
</p>
<p class="para">He jumped off the dragon's back.
    <br>His body felt incredibly light, almost weightless.
    <br>Even the longsword he had gripped with both hands felt easy to wield with just one.
    <br>He had clearly gained a power far beyond that of a mere human.
    <br>This is it, he thought, with a faint smile.
</p>
<p class="para">At the entrance leading further into the castle, a charred mass that once must have been a soldier lay in a heap.
    <br>From here on, the path narrowed—it was a place he would have to go alone.
    <br>He turned to look back at the dragon.
    <br>He was about to tell her to wait here, but stopped short in shock.
</p>
<p class="para">"……"</p>
<p class="para">His mouth froze in mid-motion, words stuck in his throat.</p>
<p class="para">"Lost your voice?""</p>
<p class="para">He had forgotten that a pact came with a price.
    <br>In exchange for the immense power, one would lose the most important bodily function to them.
    <br>And the mark of that loss would manifest as a symbol on the body.
    <br>Most likely, his own tongue bore that mark now…
</p>
<p class="para">"A sharp tongue is of no use. A light price to pay for the pact."</p>
<p class="para">The dragon said this with a hint of amusement.
    <br>Even though it was his pact partner, to the dragon, humans were nothing more than subjects of contempt.
    <br>But why?
    <br>Why had the price been his voice?
    <br>He had never placed much importance on it.
    <br>In fact, he had sometimes thought words could be nothing but trouble.
    <br>And yet, to lose it as the cost of the pact…
</p>
<p class="para">"Do not worry. I shall become your voice."</p>
<p class="para">What does that mean? I wondered if something like that was even possible, but it seemed my confusion had been understood. The dragon nodded.</p>
<p class="para">“We, as those with a pact, can exchange ‘voices’ with humans.”</p>
<p class="para"><i>Voice? But my voice was lost as the price of the pact, wasn’t it?</i></p>
<p class="para">“It is not that voice. If I were to put it in the terms of humans… it is more like ‘thoughts,’ perhaps.”</p>
<p class="para">So, does that mean she can read my mind? Indeed, we were communicating like this now.</p>
<p class="para">“I do not engage in such vile acts as peering deep into a human's heart.”</p>
<p class="para">The dragon shook her head, as if the very thought were an insult.</p>
<p class="para">"Go. I will wait here for your return."</p>
<p class="para"><i>And if I die in there? Will you just wait here forever?</i></p>
<p class="para">"If you die, I will know it at once. My life will end along with yours."</p>
<p class="para">Understood, Caim signaled with a raise of his hand. <i>Rest here. I’ll tear through them.</i> However many Imperial soldiers were inside, he would cut them down to the last.</p>
<p class="para">"You won't survive on hatred alone."</p>
<p class="para">Brushing off the dragon’s sardonic voice, Caim turned away and sprinted into the dark. <i>I’ll survive</i>, he told himself. Hatred had been enough to carry him this far. It would be enough now. Not that the gods’ exalted emissaries could ever understand the strength that human hatred could give rise to — nor did he care if they did.</p>
<p class="para">The dim corridor was littered with the bodies of fallen Union soldiers, slaughtered by the Empire. Each corpse was brutally, savagely cut down.</p>
<p class="para"><i>I’ll avenge you all. Not one of them will get away.</i></p>
<p class="para">As he moved, what he thought was just another corpse suddenly stirred. The man still clung to life.</p>
<p class="para">"The Goddess... top... floor..."</p>
<p class="para">Caim wanted to answer, but no voice came. Whether the man could still see him or not, Caim gave a small nod.</p>
<p class="para">"…Inu…art…"</p>
<p class="para"><i>Inuart? He’s here? </i>Caim crouched low, trying to catch the rest, but by then the soldier had already fallen still. Most likely, when Inuart heard that Goddess Furiae’s hiding place had been attacked, he had rushed to her side without hesitation.</p>
<p class="para">Suddenly, footsteps echoed through the passage. Caim sprang to his feet. Shadows moved at the far end.</p>
<p class="para">Imperial soldiers. Without hesitating, Caim lunged forward, driving his blade straight through. Two figures in black armor went flying. Their bodies felt strangely light — not at all like men clad in full plate.</p>
<p class="para">Even as more enemies flooded in, even as they tried to encircle him, Caim felt no fear. The soldiers moved sluggishly, their stances riddled with openings. His blade carved through them like paper. There was no sensation of cutting flesh at all — it felt more like striking at wooden posts. He felt a flash of disgust for his earlier struggle against such feeble opponents.</p>
<p class="para">So this is the power granted by the pact.</p>
<p class="para">No matter how he swung, fatigue never touched him. If anything, every slash filled him with greater strength. He could feel the twisted smile spreading across his lips. Drenched in a storm of blood, he laughed, drunk on the heavy scent of it.</p>
<p class="para">When he came back to himself, there were no enemies left. All that remained were corpses, scattered across the ground. The slaughter had taken so little time it left him almost disappointed. Still riding the last of the adrenaline, he bounded up the stairwell.</p>
<p class="para">He had never met a pact-partner before. Even though such overwhelming strength was within reach, there were still so few of them. <i>Why?</i></p>
<p class="para">The thought came to him once the fury drained away and cold reason returned.</p>
<p class="para"><i>Were they afraid of the price they’d have to pay? No. Humans weren’t so timid — nor so free of greed.</i></p>
<p class="para">Only those who harbor a bottomless darkness within can form a pact. Only those with the will to live at any cost, and the selfishness to sacrifice others to survive.</p>
<p class="para"><i>—“Negative emotions draw spirits and monsters alike.”</i></p>
<p class="para">Caim stopped in his tracks without thinking, glancing around.
    <br>He had definitely heard the dragon’s voice.
</p>
<p class="para"><i>—"Even if we are far apart, there is no difficulty in exchanging 'voices.'"</i></p>
<p class="para">If that was true, then being apart didn’t mean she couldn’t peek into his heart either.</p>
<p class="para"><i>—“How many times must I say it — I did not peek. That voice of yours is so loud, it’s impossible not to hear you. And you can’t exactly plug your ears, now can you?</i></p>
<p class="para">Her voice followed, laced with weariness.</p>
<p class="para"><i>—“Honestly. Humans…”</i></p>
<p class="para">A sigh, heavy with exasperation, echoed in his mind.</p>
<p class="para"><i>—“It’s a skill so natural that even the lowest of monsters could wield it without effort.”</i></p>
<p class="para">Ignoring the dragon's scornful voice, Caim dashed up the stairs once again.</p>
<p class="para"><i>—“Hurry. I sense something ominous.”</i></p>
<p class="para"><i>I don’t need you to tell me! Shut up!</i></p>
<p class="para">The moment he emerged from the stairwell into another corridor, an Imperial soldier leapt out, trying to ambush him.
    <br>Caim easily sidestepped and smashed the soldier’s skull. After that, there was no more sound.
</p>
<p class="para">As he reached the top of the stairs, a scream rang out.
    <br>Through the open door ahead, he could see figures — Imperial knights.
</p>
<p class="para">Unlike the common rabble crowding around the castle, Imperial Knights rarely showed themselves on the front lines.
    <br>Though Caim had fought countless battles as a mercenary, he had never crossed blades with them directly.
    <br>He had, however, seen their corpses before. Even at a glance, their distinctive armor was unmistakable.
</p>
<p class="para">—Furiae…!</p>
<p class="para">Caim sprinted at full speed.</p>
<p class="para">The short distance felt agonizingly long.</p>
<p class="para">Five knights burst from the room toward him.</p>
<p class="para">Out of my way!</p>
<p class="para">With a single sweep of his sword, he cut them all down and threw himself into the room.</p>
<p class="para">"Caim!"</p>
<p class="para">Inuart's shocked face.</p>
<p class="para">"D-Don't come any closer!"</p>
<p class="para">The last remaining knight grabbed the woman in white and shouted.
    <br>The woman, who had been staring downward, lifted her face. Her eyes widened slightly.
</p>
<p class="para">Furiae?
    <br>Furiae… is it really you?
    <br>I thought I'd never see you again in this life.
</p>
<p class="para">"If you come any closer, the goddess will—"</p>
<p class="para">Caim didn’t let him finish.</p>
<p class="para">He lunged, plunging his blade into the blood-colored eyes of the knight.
    <br>The armored body was hurled against the wall, and Caim drove the sword into the man’s throat.
</p>
<p class="para">Unforgivable. I won’t forgive you.
    <br>Six blank years—
    <br>Whose fault was it that Furiae and I had to meet again like this, in such a place?
</p>
<p class="para">Furiae’s face, drained of life like a puppet’s—
    <br>It was all because of them. Everything, all of it—
</p>
<p class="para">Again and again, Caim brought his sword down.
    <br>The armor crumpled.
    <br>The blood pooled, and he swung his blade through it without stopping.
</p>
<p class="para">"That's enough! Caim, he's already dead!"</p>
<p class="para">Inuart’s voice finally brought him back to himself.
    <br>Caim yanked his sword free from the corpse.
</p>
<p class="para">Had he scared Furiae?</p>
<p class="para">He turned—and saw her white robes soaked red with blood.</p>
<p class="para">But Furiae showed no fear.
    <br>She stood there vaguely, as if stunned.
    <br>It would have been better if terror had simply paralyzed her emotions.
    <br>Instead, her face seemed to have forgotten fear entirely.
</p>
<p class="para">The lively young girl from five years ago was nowhere to be seen.
    <br>The features were unmistakably Furiae’s.
    <br>And yet it was as if everything inside her had been hollowed out.
</p>
<p class="para">"You’re as intense as ever."</p>
<p class="para">Inuart.
    <br>Even after five years, he hadn’t changed.
    <br>But then, neither had Caim.
</p>
<p class="para">"But you saved us. Once again, I owe you my life."</p>
<p class="para">Caim opened his mouth to answer — then remembered.
    <br>He had no voice to speak with.
</p>
<p class="para">"...Hm? What’s wrong?"</p>
<p class="para">How was he supposed to explain it?</p>
<p class="para">For now, he pointed to his throat.</p>
<p class="para">Inuart only looked confused.</p>
<p class="para">Caim mimed speaking and pointed to his throat again, repeating the gesture over and over.</p>
<p class="para">"You... you lost your voice…?"</p>
<p class="para">At last, Inuart seemed to understand.</p>
<p class="para">Of course, he wouldn’t know that it was the price of the pact.
    <br>Without a word, Caim opened his mouth wide and stuck out his tongue, showing him.
</p>
<p class="para">"You mean... you’re a pact-partner?"</p>
<p class="para">Caim nodded.</p>
<p class="para">Inuart and Furiae exchanged glances.</p>
<p class="para">"I see..."</p>
<p class="para">Inuart made no attempt to hide his unease.
    <br>It seemed he hadn't changed — he was still so straightforward that it was almost foolish.
</p>
<p class="para">But Furiae showed no reaction at all.
    <br>No expression, no emotion.
</p>
<p class="para">When he thought about it, it made sense.
    <br>Furiae had been forced to abandon everything to become the Goddess of the Seal.
    <br>Compared to that, losing only his voice was nothing.
</p>
<p class="para">A heavy, suffocating silence fell between them.</p>
<p class="para">Furiae spoke hardly at all.</p>
<p class="para">And Caim—even if he wanted to—could not speak.</p>
<p class="para">Whenever Inuart fell silent, so too did the others, and the silence dragged on.</p>
<p class="para">"Hey, Caim..."</p>
<p class="para">At last, Inuart broke the quiet.</p>
<p class="para">"I’m thinking of taking Furiae to the Elf village."</p>
<p class="para">The Elf village was known for its perpetual neutrality.
    <br>A small settlement, hidden deep within the forests, yet said to be as well-defended as any fortress.
</p>
<p class="para">"If we take her there, the Imperial army shouldn’t be able to reach her so easily."</p>
<p class="para">Was that really true?
    <br>Could they be so sure that a village's neutrality would guarantee safety?
</p>
<p class="para">"To escort a goddess around like this is an act of grave impiety... but we have no choice, do we?"</p>
<p class="para">It was true.
    <br>The fall of this castle was only a matter of time.
    <br>They had to get Furiae out—find a safe haven for her as soon as possible.
</p>
<p class="para">"She was once my betrothed," Inuart said quietly. "I can't let her die."</p>
<p class="para">The word "betrothed" pricked at Caim’s chest, if only slightly.</p>
<p class="para">"She's your beloved sister too, isn’t she?" Inuart added. "Before she's the Goddess, she's still Furiae."</p>
<p class="para">Once Inuart made up his mind, there was no changing it.
    <br>Caim had known that since they were children.
    <br>But what about Furiae herself?
</p>
<p class="para">Caim shifted his gaze to her.</p>
<p class="para">"I suppose I must continue living," she said.</p>
<p class="para">Her voice was flat, devoid of any feeling.
    <br>Inuart's words had stirred no visible reaction.
</p>
<p class="para">"As the Goddess that maintains the world's seal."</p>
<p class="para">She spoke as though it were someone else's life, someone else's duty.</p>
<p class="para">For a moment, Caim glimpsed the years she must have endured alone.</p>
<p class="para">"It's all right, isn't it?"</p>
<p class="para">Caim nodded. Then shrugged his shoulders in resignation.
    <br>Whatever he might say, Inuart would not listen anyway.
</p>
<p class="para">"I see," Inuart said, smiling in relief.
    <br>He picked up a fallen chair nearby and set it upright.
</p>
<p class="para">"Then let’s have a toast."</p>
<p class="para">He spoke playfully, lifting a harp in his hands.
    <br>Caim frowned.
    <br>Was this really the time for such nonsense?
</p>
<p class="para">"Take a moment to rest," Inuart said.
    <br>"You’ve been running nonstop until now, haven’t you?"
</p>
<p class="para">His fingers brushed against the harp strings.
    <br>A melody filled the room—gentle and nostalgic.
</p>
<p class="para">It had been so long since Caim had heard that sound.
    <br>No doubt, the same was true for Furiae.
</p>
<p class="para">Maybe this was enough, for now.</p>
<p class="para">The sweet strains of the harp drifted through the air.
    <br>It felt, almost, like they had returned to the past.
</p>
<p class="para">Of course, the bloodshed continued downstairs, and the three of them were no longer innocent children.
    <br>Even so...
</p>
<p class="para">Caim turned his eyes toward Furiae.</p>
<p class="para">Her face, so hollow and lifeless before, now seemed touched by a faint, fleeting calm.</p>
